":[{"name":"Pabenham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Pakenham (Suffolk). The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pacca</i> (genitive <i>Paccan</i>) + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’.","History: A family of this name has been established in Westmeath, Ireland, since the 16th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When John II Pabenham was born in 1219, in Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh II de Pabenham, was 32 and his mother, Eleanor, was 29. He had at least 2 sons with Eleanor de St Remy. He died in 1248, in his hometown, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1219–1248":"1219–1248","1219–1264":"1219–1264","1217–1248":"1217–1248","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1248–1322":"1248–1322","1187–1237":"1187–1237","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","before 1248":"enne 1248","1190":"1190","1217":"1217","1237":"1237","1248":"1248","1322":"1322","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","1264":"1264","about 1242":"umbes 1242","before 1219":"enne 1219","1219":"1219","Pabenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1219–1248":"1219–1248","1219–1264":"1219–1264","1217–1248":"1217–1248","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1248–1322":"1248–1322","1187–1237":"1187–1237","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","before 1248":"ennen vuotta 1248","1190":"1190","1217":"1217","1237":"1237","1248":"1248","1322":"1322","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","1264":"1264","about 1242":"noin 1242","before 1219":"ennen vuotta 1219","1219":"1219","Pabenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1219–1248":"1219–1248","1219–1264":"1219–1264","1217–1248":"1217–1248","1242–Male":"1242–Décédé","1248–1322":"1248–1322","1187–1237":"1187–1237","1190–Female":"1190–Décédée","before 1248":"avant 1248","1190":"119